I can't reproduce that on Linux:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/15164633/48237521-f7642300-e394-11e8-88f4-e9bb0ab87395.png)
I'm also using Stata 15 and `stata-kernel` version 1.6.2

I was suspecting that it has conflicts with Chrome extensions or Jupyter Extensions. But I was able to reproduce it in Firefox with all Jupyter and Firefox Extension disabled.

By the way, using PDF graph format does not have this issue.
Can you open the svg itself? Look in whatever your Stata kernel cache folder is.
That's weird. The SVG itself seems fine.

![2018-11-08 21 33 17](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/2144783/48241813-12876080-e39e-11e8-934d-16140ecaeaf9.gif)

This is funny. It must be a front-end issue...

I can actually reproduce this on Mac in Chrome.

Have you found this with any other command than `vioplot`? I'm wondering if there's a bug in that command, since it's user developed.

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/15164633/48276576-5453ed80-e416-11e8-9d07-4302700073a9.png)

No, I haven't found other commands that have this bug so far. I am guessing that the SVG is using the same path same across different plots, and they are interfering each other.

I am quite surprised that this is OS-related.

You'll see this any time you load multiple graphs with a shaded portion:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/15164633/48279038-5bcac500-e41d-11e8-8fd0-93689b720239.png)

I can also reproduce this on Windows:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/15164633/48279104-8fa5ea80-e41d-11e8-8dd6-24ba0d7b37b1.png)
I don't know if there's a way for me to reliably try to fix this... really seems like it's Stata's fault. I might email them a bug report later. @mcaceresb 	any comment?
Replace all instances of `xlink:href` with `href`?
Actually it appears that isn't the issue
Is it possible to put an iframe to wrap the SVG up?

This is actually completely cross platform. Linux:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/15164633/48282159-dcda8a00-e426-11e8-93f5-5d9aff2051ef.png)

Even persists in Atom on Linux:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/15164633/48282210-114e4600-e427-11e8-9eff-0e727249fd08.png)

@mcaceresb 	
@alanzchen 	

Here's the output of the above two graphs: https://github.com/kylebarron/stata_kernel/tree/issue-234/issues/234.

Here's the issue. Every time that Stata exports an SVG, any shaded region is defined as `id="path1"`, and then is included on the rest of the graph through the import `<use xlink:href="#path1"/>`. It actually doesn't matter whether you use `xlink:href` or just `href`. When there are multiple SVG elements defined with the same ID, it appears that only the first one is found when a reference is made to it. So the `<use xlink:href="#path1"/>` on the second graph finds the definition of `path1` on the _first_ graph, not the second.

https://github.com/kylebarron/stata_kernel/blob/f4d107ea1b2be79f44c870f22e1e71f80a0b1a85/issues/234/price_weight_Unix.svg#L17-L24

It's technically conceivable that I could try to replace the `use` statement with whatever the correct definition is _before sending it to Jupyter_, which would solve the problem, but that's not necessarily easy nor guaranteed to be without side effects. I don't want to be messing up peoples' graphs.

> Is it possible to put an iframe to wrap the SVG up?

I just return the SVG data to Jupyter. Jupyter's frontends decide how to handle it. I can't return it as an `iframe` myself.
